IMPORTANT — READ THIS ENTIRE AGREEMENT BEFORE ACCESSING, READING, CLONING,
EXECUTING, DEPLOYING, OR INTERACTING WITH THE PLANIT BACKEND APPLICATION OR
ANY PART OF ITS INFRASTRUCTURE.

This License Agreement ("Agreement") is a legally binding contract between You
and Aakshat Hariharan ("Author") governing Your access to and use of the PlanIt
backend application — the server-side engine that powers all data persistence,
business logic, authentication, authorization, real-time communication,
external integrations, and API services for the PlanIt platform.

The backend services embody years of architectural decisions, security
engineering, proprietary data models, and integration logic that represent
the core commercial value of the PlanIt platform. Unauthorized access to,
copying of, deployment of, or derivation from this software constitutes not
only a breach of this Agreement but may also give rise to civil copyright
infringement claims and, depending on the method of access, potential criminal
liability under computer fraud and abuse statutes.

By reading, running, or interacting with this code in any form, You agree to
be bound by this Agreement in its entirety.

================================================================================
SECTION 1 — DEFINITIONS
================================================================================

1.1   "Backend Application" or "Software" means the PlanIt server-side
      application in its entirety, including without limitation:

      (a)  The main Express.js application server file (server.js) and all
           middleware registered therein, including security middleware,
           maintenance guard, CORS configuration, rate limiting, compression,
           trust proxy settings, and error handling;

      (b)  All route handler files under /routes/, including but not limited
           to routes for events, authentication, public data, admin operations,
           white-label management, white-label client portal, seating charts,
           uptime monitoring, file upload handling, and all future routes;

      (c)  All Mongoose schema definitions and model files under /models/,
           including the Event, WhiteLabel, WLLead, EventParticipant, Incident,
           MaintenanceSchedule, and all other data models and their validators,
           virtuals, middleware hooks, and indexes;

      (d)  All middleware files under /middleware/, including the trafficGuard
           security middleware, rate limiters, upload scanners, error handlers,
           and authentication verifiers;

      (e)  All service modules under /services/, including the email service
           (Brevo/Mailjet integrations), notification service (ntfy.sh, Discord
           webhook), cryptographic license key generation and verification
           service, and any other integration services;

      (f)  The proprietary license key cryptographic system, including the
           HMAC-based key format specification (WL-{TIER}-{DOMAIN_HASH}-
           {EXPIRY_HEX}-{HMAC_12}), the key generation logic, the key
           verification algorithm, and all associated secret management;

      (g)  The white-label resolution, heartbeat verification, and license
           enforcement logic, including the domain-based lookup, suspension
           handling, CORS domain registration, and billing status enforcement;

      (h)  The Socket.IO real-time event communication layer, including room
           management, event broadcasting, participant state synchronization,
           table service real-time updates, and chat message delivery;

      (i)  All configuration files, environment variable schemas, seed scripts,
           database migration utilities, and operational tooling;

      (j)  All documentation, code comments, architectural notes, and inline
           specifications embedded in or accompanying the Backend Application.

1.2   "Author" means Aakshat Hariharan, the sole architect, developer, and
      intellectual property owner of the Backend Application, its data models,
      cryptographic systems, and all business logic embodied therein.

1.3   "You" or "Licensee" means any individual, developer, engineer, data
      scientist, security researcher, organization, company, partnership,
      corporation, government entity, educational institution, non-profit, or
      any other natural or legal person that in any way accesses, reads,
      downloads, clones, deploys, executes, queries, penetration-tests,
      benchmarks, reverse engineers, or otherwise interacts with the Backend
      Application or any component thereof.

1.4   "Hosted Service" means the publicly accessible deployment of the PlanIt
      platform operated by the Author, including the backend instances
      (Maverick, Goose, Iceman, Slider, Viper) reachable through the Router
      Service at planitapp.onrender.com and associated domains.

1.5   "Cryptographic License System" means the proprietary white-label license
      key generation and verification system embedded in the Backend Application,
      including the key format specification, the HMAC-SHA256 proof chain
      algorithm, the domain hash derivation function, the expiry encoding
      scheme, and all secrets required to operate it.

1.6   "Data Models" means the Mongoose schema definitions, field specifications,
      validation rules, indexing strategies, middleware hooks, and all associated
      database design decisions embodied in the /models/ directory, which
      constitute proprietary business logic and trade secrets of the Author.

1.7   "API Surface" means the complete set of HTTP endpoints, their request
      schemas, response formats, authentication requirements, rate limiting
      configurations, and behavioral specifications defined by the Backend
      Application.

1.8   "Derivative Work" means any software, service, API, backend system, data
      model, schema, or other work that: (a) is derived from, copies, or adapts
      any portion of the Backend Application; (b) reimplements the Data Models,
      Cryptographic License System, or API Surface; (c) replicates the
      architectural patterns, security mechanisms, or business logic; or
      (d) could serve as a drop-in or functional replacement for the Backend
      Application.

1.9   "Deploy" means to execute, run, serve, containerize, orchestrate, or
      operate the Backend Application or any portion thereof on any computing
      infrastructure including local development machines, cloud platforms
      (AWS, GCP, Azure, Render, Railway, Fly.io, etc.), VPS, shared hosting,
      Kubernetes clusters, serverless functions, or any other environment.

1.10  "Commercial Use" means any deployment, use, or exploitation of the
      Backend Application in connection with any commercial or revenue-
      generating activity, including operating a competing SaaS, providing
      consulting services, building client projects, or powering any paid
      product or service.

1.11  "Penetration Testing" means any deliberate attempt to probe, test, scan,
      or otherwise assess the security of the Hosted Service or any Backend
      Application instance beyond normal user interaction, including but not
      limited to vulnerability scanning, SQL injection attempts, authentication
      bypass attempts, API fuzzing, and rate limit circumvention.

